Fred Burton quoted David Weber as saying:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Simon &amp; Schuster, on the other hand, would really
&gt; prefer to see nothing but Honor novels, in an unending succession, and I'm
&gt; not sure exactly how that's going to play out.
">

We can certainly understand their motivation here.

Sadly, of course, that probably isn't going to be possible.
Personally, although I enjoyed the most recent novel, &quot;At All Costs&quot;,
I felt that to some extent the overall plot was stalled - to a limited
extent, it could be considered as partly a re-hash of War of Honor.

Given the plot threads in &quot;Crown of Slaves&quot;, I noted one way in which
you might be planning to get out of the corner in which you might seem
to be painted - basically, given that the battles of the last two
novels with Haven were essentially needless, and instigated by the
forces of genetic slavery, the *main* charactor, Honor Harrington,
should somehow be fighting the *main* battle. Even though her forte is
fighting a different kind of battle.

The reason the first 10 books in the series were so compelling, of
course, is that they weren't *just* full of rip-roaring space battles.
We had a very sympathetic character, who experienced personal
tragedies, and despite setbacks, achieved the rewards she earned.

A story like that has to move forwards. It can't go around in circles
without becoming a different kind of story. There are ups and downs,
but they still add up to net progress. So, such a story leads to a
natural conclusion. Another down, and then an up, is probably all that
is left before things become interminable and thus ridiculous.

If all good things must come to an end, though, how will you and Simon
and Schuster support yourselves in the style to which you have become
accustomed?

There _is_ a way to keep doing the same thing over again without
letting it become stale.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;From the work of a very famous and successful author - whose work,
">

though, was more archetypal but also more formulaic than yours - this
can be called the Llana of Gathol strategy.

With novels like &quot;Shadow of Saganami&quot; and &quot;Crown of Slaves&quot;, you have
told very different kinds of stories in the Honorverse. The
protagonists of those stories have appeared also in the Honor
Harrington novels.

Other people who have appeared in these novels, however, are junior
officers in the Manticore naval forces who are on the command track.
Their stories won't be exactly like Honor's story, but they can
continue on while Honor herself has gone on to what is effectively a
well-deserved retirement. (Of course, between prolong and her sense of
duty, Honor is not going to retire, but she is going to get promoted
to a desk job pretty soon.)

And there are also NCOs whose stories have crossed Honor's path. So
one can tell a story that is different, but less different, from
Honor's than those in the sidestreams.

So one can avoid attempting to prolong (pardon the expression) Honor
Harrington's own story beyond the bounds of reason, and yet continue
to produce novels with nearly the proven commercial value of the Honor
Harrington novels themselves.

John Savard
