.
Originally, because perhaps of the order in which I read the books at
first, my recollection of some items was somewhat confused.

So I somewhat unfairly perceived &quot;At All Costs&quot; as a near-rehash of
&quot;War of Honor&quot;. I see now that both books had their necessary place in
the story.

Since the &quot;real&quot; conflict is that between everyone and Mesa,
originally I had suggested that perhaps the next book should have
Honor Harrington run off with Lester Tourville - and do what Anton
Zilwicki and Victor Cachat are already doing. Since she is the &quot;hero&quot;,
she should be the one fighting the main enemy.

The next book coming out in the Honorverse will be more of the *side*
story. So things are moving to the point where Haven and Manticore
will have the *one thing* that can bring peace between them after so
much bloodshed and without victory by either side... a common enemy.
And if you think Elizabeth III is angry at _Haven_... her anger at
being played for a fool will be even greater, although, to her credit,
she will have learned her lesson, and not permit her emotions to make
her decisions for her. She will expend her fury in private so as not
to lose her dignity - and then her anger shall become a cold anger,
terrifying and majestic...and which Honor's special relationship with
her treecat will give David Weber an opportunity to describe.

Honor, commanding the six hundred or so remaining Havenite
dreadnoughts, combined with the shattered remnants of Manticoran,
Grayson, and (perhaps) Andermanni navies, defend Manticore, and Haven,
against an attack *by the Solarian League* instigated by Mesa? (And
how do they do it - frame Manticore for a violation of the Eridani
Edict?)

That would certainly allow a next novel fitting well into the previous
pattern.

But while &quot;At All Costs&quot; might not be justly described as a rehash of
&quot;War of Honor&quot;, there is still a danger of repetition; and &quot;At All
Costs&quot; has another flaw given its presumed readership - it tries a bit
too hard to engage *sentiment* in the reader. (At least, though, that
is change. The naval battles are exciting, but they aren't everything.
The human story and the political intrigue are important ingredients.)

Alternatively: if peace breaks out between Manticore and Haven, people
might *blame* Elizabeth III for things coming to Beatrice - as if what
happened on Torch wouldn't fool anyone - and we have Manticore and,
for different reasons, Haven, in a position of weakness, to deal with
a smaller threat - say elements of the OFS under Mesan control?

Repeating the cycle - and having Honor experience a setback, so that
she needs to start over again, as in &quot;Flag in Exile&quot; or &quot;Echoes of
Honor&quot; - is risky. Particularly after a book like &quot;At All Costs&quot;.
There are plot threads which mean that lots of exciting things can
still happen, but so much _has_ happened to Honor that extending the
saga in *some* ways will feel like cheating the reader. David Weber
intends to avoid this, as can be seen from the series as it exists so
far; but with Honor herself, it's going to get harder and harder to
manage. But then, I may be underestimating his talent.

John Savard
