Except that the RMN does not have enough pods, nor does it have the
capacity to make enough.  The SLN is really that big.  Even with
Apollo, it takes more than one pod to take out an SD.

The truly frightening thought is that The Crippler (from &quot;With One
Stone&quot;) is a piece of solly tech.  It would not have been developed as
far as it was, if it was not good for something.  The Crippler is very
nearly useless as a an anti-ship weapon, but it simply rocks as a
point defence weapon (with a range of one million kilometers).  Using
Apollo forces the missiles to bunch up, which makes them even better
crippler targets

The sollie stealthed missile is not useful, by itself, but Manpower
has some nasty clandestine ops capabilities that may be able to get
tracking beacons onto a number of RMN vessels.

Apollo is nothing more than a recon drone with a two-way FTL link that
allows the missiles to use the launching ships' ECCM computer to
counter the target's ECM, instead of the missiles' more limited
capabilities (Not that it is spelled out anywhere, but that is the
only possibility that makes any sense).  The only tricks are making
the grav pulse generators directional and small enough.  If you do not
care about stealth and efficiency, you just jury-rig the comm link by
modulating the recon drone's drive and the return signal is by
modulating the ship's drive.  It can probably be jammed, but a home-on-
jam feature allow some missiles to still pierce RMN counter-measures.

There would be little point to telegraphing a showdown between the RMN
and SLN, if there was no doubt about the outcome.
